He remarks to Lentulus that he has now almost entirely given up composing speeches, and has returned to his youthful love, the humane letters.

He had indeed for some time lived entirely with- drawn from public life, where even previously he had lost all power of influencing the course of affairs. In 63 13.c. the oligarchical party had been glad to make use of his legal and oratorical talents in the suppres- sion of the conspiracy of Catiline ; but they were not willing to make any sacrifices in order to repay him for his services, and in 58 B.c. they allowed Clodius to procure his banishment in punishment for the alleged illegality of his procedure in the Catilinarian affair. A year later Pompeius, finding Clodius more dangerous, again required Cicero’s assistance, and procured his recall from exile.
